original email:
El Paso declared an Unauthorized Overpull Penalty situation Thursday that 
will remain in effect until further notice. The pipeline said it will limit 
scheduled volumes at underperforming interconnects to insure system 
integrity. 
Likely in response to the A/BC border constraint that began Thursday due to 
maintenance on the TransCanada-British Columbia Line, NOVA changed its 
imbalance tolerance range to +2%/-18% Wednesday. Reflecting the resultant 
shift in supply accessibility, neighboring Westcoast has a +20%/0% tolerance 
in effect.
revised email: Hey there! Just wanted to give you a heads up that El Paso has declared an Unauthorized Overpull Penalty situation, which will be in effect until further notice. The pipeline will be limiting scheduled volumes at underperforming interconnects to ensure system integrity. This is likely due to the A/BC border constraint that began on Thursday due to maintenance on the TransCanada-British Columbia Line. As a result, NOVA has changed its imbalance tolerance range to +2%/-18% on Wednesday, and neighboring Westcoast has a +20%/0% tolerance in effect. Just wanted to keep you informed on the situation.

original email:
Karen - RE the Q below -  
	Will I still receive severance if the company files bankruptcy?
Draft Answer - It is unlikely that severance payments would be continued.   Current or former employees of a bankrupt entity are generally considered as unsecured creditors, in line with other unsecured creditors.  Employee claims will generally be represented through a court designated trustee.
revised email:
Hello Karen.
I received your question about severance pay in the event of employment termination. For your records, I'll repeat your question below:
"Will I still receive severance if the company files bankruptcy?"
To answer your question, it is unfortunately unlikely that severance payments would continue in the event of bankruptcy of the company. The general policy is that current or former employees of a bankrupt entity are considered as unsecured creditors, in line with other unsecured creditors. Due to this, employee claims will generally be represented through a court designated trustee. Please let me know if this answers your question, or if you need further information.
